s and social movements of our time, The Politics of Ritual examines a broad range of rituals enacted to just and democratic ends, including border Eucharists, candlelight vigils, and rituals of mourning. This timely book makes a persuasive case for an innovative democratic ritual life that can enable people to create and sustain communities that are more just, inclusive, and participatory than those in which they find themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aRites and ceremoniesxPolitical aspects. 0aRitualxPolitical aspects. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  ademocracy.  aliturgy.  aprotest.  areligion and politics.  aritual.  asocial movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691248929?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691248929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691248929/original  a978-3-11-074974-8  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK